        "title": "Chapter 22: The Tracking",
        "content": "<p>Kyle came back through pain.</p>\n<p>Not all at once.</p>\n<p>First the floor.</p>\n<p>Cold under his cheek. Sticky where coffee had dried. Grit in the corner of his mouth. A shard of ceramic under his palm, not deep, only enough to make the hand useless when he tried to close it.</p>\n<p>Then sound.</p>\n<p>Water ticking somewhere. Bobi breathing too fast. The dog whining in short cuts, stopping every time Kyle moved. Street noise above and below, ordinary city machinery continuing as if no room had been opened and emptied.</p>\n<p>Then smell.</p>\n<p>Blood. Coffee. Damp rope. Gerard's coat, clean even in absence, a faint expensive wool trace that did not belong to the safehouse.</p>\n<p>Kyle opened his eyes.</p>\n<p>The room tilted left. He let it. Tilt meant head. Head meant time lost. Time lost meant distance.</p>\n<p>Eline was gone.</p>\n<p>The thought tried to become feeling.</p>\n<p>He killed it.</p>\n<p>Not dead.</p>\n<p>Not useful.</p>\n<p>Later.</p>\n<p>His hand was closed around the lighter.</p>\n<p>He did not remember closing it. The plastic had bitten a crescent into his palm. Cheap blue casing. Scratched edge. Still there.</p>\n<p>He moved his thumb over the wheel.</p>\n<p>Once.</p>\n<p>No flame.</p>\n<p>Just proof.</p>\n<p>Bobi knelt beside him. His mouth moved. Kyle watched the shape of words and did not take them in. The old man had blood on his sleeve and fear in the tendons of his neck. The dog had dragged himself half under Kyle's arm and left a dark smear from the bandage across the floorboards.</p>\n<p>Kyle sat up.</p>\n<p>The room broke white.</p>\n<p>He folded forward over his knees and did not vomit.</p>\n<p>Bobi's hand hovered near his shoulder.</p>\n<p>Kyle shook his head once.</p>\n<p>Bad idea. The room shifted. He held still until the walls returned to their corners.</p>\n<p>Three men.</p>\n<p>One pistol.</p>\n<p>One inside lock compromised.</p>\n<p>One route out.</p>\n<p>He turned his head by degrees. Table. Door. Window. Rope. Knife. Keys. Blood in the towel. Coffee track. Mud print near the threshold. Not Bobi's. Not his. Narrow sole. Clean tread. Left foot turned out half a degree because expensive shoes lied badly on old stairs.</p>\n<p>Gerard.</p>\n<p>Kyle crawled to the door before he stood.</p>\n<p>He used the table leg. Then the wall. Then nothing, because nothing was faster.</p>\n<p>His body wanted a doctor.</p>\n<p>It got work.</p>\n<p>The hallway held the first answer. Old smoke. Damp plaster. A chalk sun near the stairwell with teeth drawn in yellow. Below it, a smear where someone had brushed the wall with Eline's sleeve or shoulder. Pale dust disturbed at hip height. Not dragged. Walking. Resisting enough to be steered.</p>\n<p>Alive.</p>\n<p>The word tried to open him.</p>\n<p>He closed around it.</p>\n<p>Alive was direction.</p>\n<p>Down two flights. Not the front. Too visible. Service door. Alley.</p>\n<p>Kyle took Bobi's keys from the table without asking. Bobi did not stop him. The dog tried to follow and failed at the first step, nails scraping, rope catching under a chair.</p>\n<p>Kyle looked back once.</p>\n<p>The animal's eyes were bright with useless fury.</p>\n<p>Good.</p>\n<p>Something in the room still knew how to hate.</p>\n<p>Outside, the city hit him hard enough to steady him.</p>\n<p>Diesel. Rain in drains. Rot under market crates. Old bread. Cigarettes. A delivery bike chained badly to a post. Three windows open above the alley, one curtain twitching too late. Gerard's men would trust cameras, clean routes, drivers, booked corridors, people paid to look away.</p>\n<p>Kyle trusted bad habits.</p>\n<p>He found the tire mark at the mouth of the alley. Long wheelbase. Heavy enough to shine the wet cobbles. Not police. Not taxi. Private car taking the lane too wide because the driver did not know the delivery rut near the butcher's back door.</p>\n<p>He followed the wrongness.</p>\n<p>No phone.</p>\n<p>Phones left records. Phones waited for networks. Phones told rich men where fear was standing.</p>\n<p>He used glass.</p>\n<p>Bakery window, dark enough to catch the street behind him. Pharmacy door. Bus shelter panel cracked across the middle. Puddles where the rain had stopped but traffic kept moving. Each reflection gave him pieces: clean sedan turning east, one man in the back with his hand low, a pale face between shoulders for half a second before the car moved behind a tram.</p>\n<p>Eline.</p>\n<p>His knee almost failed at the tram stop.</p>\n<p>He caught the pole with his bad hand.</p>\n<p>The shard cut deeper.</p>\n<p>Pain cleared the street.</p>\n<p>Good.</p>\n<p>He walked faster.</p>\n<p>Gerard's route avoided cameras until it did not. That was the arrogance of systems. They believed blind spots belonged to whoever paid for them. They forgot delivery boys smoked under dead lenses. Forgot old women watched from third floors because sleep had left them years ago. Forgot dogs barked at cars that smelled wrong.</p>\n<p>Kyle did not ask questions.</p>\n<p>He watched answers.</p>\n<p>A cigarette dropped half-smoked near a curb where no one stood. The driver had waited there. A black thread caught on a rusted gate. Dark coat. Expensive wool. A parking bollard pushed out of line by a vehicle too impatient to reverse twice. East, then south. Not the Estate. Not yet.</p>\n<p>Transfer.</p>\n<p>Move the asset before the house became searchable. Move her through a place with locks, water, and no witnesses who mattered.</p>\n<p>Old canal warehouses.</p>\n<p>He knew the district because nobody important did. Loading bays. Night storage. Rotting rope. Men paid cash to forget plates. Water deep enough to remove evidence and shallow enough to smell like it.</p>\n<p>His head rang.</p>\n<p>He put a hand against a wall, let two breaths pass, and tasted iron from the cut inside his mouth.</p>\n<p>Routes.</p>\n<p>Main road: watched.</p>\n<p>Bridge: visible.</p>\n<p>Canal edge: slow, exposed.</p>\n<p>Back lane through the print shop, if the owner still kept the rear shutter broken.</p>\n<p>He went through the print shop.</p>\n<p>The shutter gave under his shoulder with a wet metal shriek. A light came on somewhere above him. Kyle was already past the bins, over the low wall, into the strip of dead ground between buildings where moss grew black and glass crunched underfoot.</p>\n<p>His body became smaller there.</p>\n<p>Not less hurt.</p>\n<p>Less seen.</p>\n<p>He moved through rubbish, laundry lines, a courtyard with broken chairs stacked under a tarp, a passage narrow enough to scrape both shoulders. The city marked him and hid him at the same time. Mud up one leg. Blood dried at his neck. Coffee stiffening his sleeve. No clean silhouette. Nothing worth a camera keeping.</p>\n<p>At the final corner, he stopped.</p>\n<p>Across the canal, the warehouse stood with three lit windows and one van backed to the side entrance.</p>\n<p>Clean van.</p>\n<p>Wrong for the street.</p>\n<p>A man stood by it, smoking without tasting the smoke.</p>\n<p>Another waited near the water gate.</p>\n<p>Gerard would be inside.</p>\n<p>Eline would be inside or being moved.</p>\n<p>Kyle checked his pocket.</p>\n<p>Keys. Lighter. No weapon worth naming.</p>\n<p>He looked at the warehouse, the water, the broken loading crane, the iron ladder bolted into the canal wall, the old fire door warped by damp at the hinge.</p>\n<p>Bad idea.</p>\n<p>Only one.</p>\n<p>He put the lighter in his front pocket where a hand could find it fast.</p>\n<p>Then he climbed down to the waterline and disappeared under the lip of the canal wall.</p>"
