        "title": "Chapter 24: The Canal / The Artifact",
        "content": "<p>The canal did not receive her.</p>\n<p>It was simply there.</p>\n<p>Black water. Flat light. Concrete slick with old rain. Mud at the edge where the paving stones had given up holding a straight line. A bottle moved under the bridge, tapped once against the wall, and drifted on without meaning anything by it.</p>\n<p>Eline stood alone beside the water.</p>\n<p>Not because they had let her go.</p>\n<p>Because systems had seams, too.</p>\n<p>Because Gerard's arm had hung wrong after the hook. Because the pistol had gone into the canal. Because the men outside had looked first to Gerard and then to the water and then to the blood on the warehouse floor, and in that thin confusion Eline had walked through the loading door with Kyle's lighter in her fist.</p>\n<p>Walked.</p>\n<p>Not run.</p>\n<p>Running would have made her a body to catch.</p>\n<p>Walking had made her a mistake in the room's accounting.</p>\n<p>Now the warehouse was behind her, out of sight beyond the bend. Voices had come and gone. One siren had risen far away, then another. The city did not arrange itself around any of it.</p>\n<p>A cyclist passed on the bridge above.</p>\n<p>Somewhere a man shouted about a delivery.</p>\n<p>Rainwater dripped from a pipe into the canal in slow, dirty ticks.</p>\n<p>Eline's hands were red to the wrists.</p>\n<p>Some of it had dried. Some had cracked when she closed her fingers. Under the blood, the lighter was still blue. Cheap plastic. Scratched edge. Kyle's thumb mark worn into the wheel where metal met skin over and over until a small fire agreed to happen.</p>\n<p>She opened her hand.</p>\n<p>The lighter lay across her palm.</p>\n<p>Not a relic.</p>\n<p>Not yet.</p>\n<p>Relics belonged to houses like hers. Glass cases. Labels. Dust arranged by people paid to remember correctly.</p>\n<p>This was a tool.</p>\n<p>It smelled faintly of fuel and Kyle's pocket and the warehouse floor. It had no dignity. It had survived because he had closed his hand around it after Gerard struck him. Because he had carried it through blood and alley water and bad decisions. Because, at the end, he had spent his last clear movement putting it into her hand.</p>\n<p>Eline's knees wanted to fold.</p>\n<p>She let them.</p>\n<p>The mud took her weight.</p>\n<p>Cold went through the silk of the nightdress, through the torn sleeve, through the skin of her legs. Her burned fingertips stung. Her bruised arm throbbed. Her palms hurt where the chain had torn them. Her throat hurt from the sound she had made when Kyle fell.</p>\n<p>Her body listed the damage without mercy.</p>\n<p>Good.</p>\n<p>She was still in it.</p>\n<p>Across the canal, a window opened. Someone leaned out, smoked, went back inside. The smoke did not rise beautifully. The wind flattened it and broke it apart.</p>\n<p>Eline looked at the water.</p>\n<p>If she softened her eyes, the black surface could become glass.</p>\n<p>She did not soften them.</p>\n<p>The water was water. Dirty. Cold. Moving where the current forced it. Carrying the city in fragments: oil, cigarette ends, a leaf browned to lace, the pistol somewhere below if the canal had not already swallowed it into silt.</p>\n<p>Kyle was not in the water.</p>\n<p>Kyle was on the warehouse floor.</p>\n<p>Kyle was in the red drying under her nails.</p>\n<p>Kyle was in the ugly blue object in her palm.</p>\n<p>Kyle was not coming.</p>\n<p>The sentence entered her like cold air.</p>\n<p>All the way down.</p>\n<p>She waited for the room to flatten. For distance to save her. For the old glass pane to slide between her skin and the world.</p>\n<p>It did not come.</p>\n<p>Nothing saved her.</p>\n<p>The mud pressed under her knees. The canal stank. A gull screamed from a roofline. Her teeth began to chatter so hard her jaw hurt. The wind found the wet places in her clothes and kept touching them.</p>\n<p>Eline made herself close her fingers around the lighter.</p>\n<p>The wheel was small.</p>\n<p>Hostile.</p>\n<p>It did not care what she had lost.</p>\n<p>She set her thumb to it.</p>\n<p>The first strike failed.</p>\n<p>Metal rasped. No flame.</p>\n<p>Her thumb slipped because of the blood.</p>\n<p>She laughed.</p>\n<p>The sound came out broken, almost silent, and disappeared over the water.</p>\n<p>Of course.</p>\n<p>Of course it would not give her warmth because she needed it. Nothing real worked that way.</p>\n<p>She wiped her thumb against the nightdress. White silk took red, black, grey. The house would have destroyed the garment for less. The thought moved through her and found no place to sit.</p>\n<p>She struck again.</p>\n<p>Spark.</p>\n<p>No flame.</p>\n<p>Her thumb hurt.</p>\n<p>Again.</p>\n<p>The wheel tore a little skin loose.</p>\n<p>Again.</p>\n<p>The flame caught.</p>\n<p>Small.</p>\n<p>Shaking.</p>\n<p>Yellow at the throat, blue near the metal, bent sideways by the canal wind.</p>\n<p>Eline cupped her other hand around it.</p>\n<p>Not to make it pretty.</p>\n<p>To keep it alive.</p>\n<p>The heat touched the blood in her palm first. Then the raw place on her thumb. Then the air beneath her chin. Barely anything. Almost nothing.</p>\n<p>Enough to hurt.</p>\n<p>Enough to prove itself.</p>\n<p>She looked at the flame until her eyes watered from wind and smoke.</p>\n<p>Kyle had not saved her from grief.</p>\n<p>He had made grief unable to take her body away from her.</p>\n<p>That was not mercy.</p>\n<p>It was more difficult than mercy.</p>\n<p>The flame guttered.</p>\n<p>She protected it.</p>\n<p>Her shoulders shook now. Not from cold only. Her mouth opened and the sound came, ugly, human, uncontrolled. It bent her over the lighter. It put salt on her lips. It pulled at the place behind her ribs until she thought something might tear open and keep tearing forever.</p>\n<p>No one corrected her.</p>\n<p>No one measured the sound.</p>\n<p>No one came to make her clean.</p>\n<p>The canal did not comfort her. The city did not witness her with tenderness. The water did not carry Kyle back.</p>\n<p>It was all still there anyway.</p>\n<p>Concrete. Mud. Blood. Flame. Breath.</p>\n<p>Eline stayed.</p>\n<p>When the lighter grew hot against her thumb, she let the flame die.</p>\n<p>Smoke rose in a thin line and vanished almost immediately.</p>\n<p>She did not.</p>\n<p>After a while, she stood.</p>\n<p>Mud clung to her knees. Blood stiffened her fingers. The cold remained. The grief remained. The lighter sat in her hand with no promise inside it except the one it had always made.</p>\n<p>Strike.</p>\n<p>Friction.</p>\n<p>Fuel, if there was any.</p>\n<p>Warmth, if she protected it.</p>\n<p>Eline put the lighter in her pocket and turned from the canal.</p>\n<p>Behind her, the water kept moving.</p>"
